WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
In this video, I'll walk through the process of using Shiny Assistant to quickly prototype a Shiny app that uses TidyTuesday data.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:16.000
TidyTuesday is a weekly social data project. Each week, the TidyTuesday team posts a new dataset to their GitHub repository.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:23.000
You can then explore the data and post your visualization, model, dashboard, app, etc. to social media to share with others.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:31.000
In collaboration with TidyTuesday, Posit hosts PydyTuesday, an initiative to help people get started with TidyTuesday and Python.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
You can check out the other videos in this playlist to learn more.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Today, I'll demonstrate one task you might want to do with the TidyTuesday data, create a Shiny app.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
And I'm going to do so with the help of Shiny Assistant, an AI-powered tool designed to help you quickly build Shiny apps.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:51.000
You can think of Shiny Assistant like a knowledgeable colleague ready to help you with Shiny.

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Okay, so let's get started. Before I start building the Shiny app, let's take a look at the TidyTuesday data.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
So this is the TidyTuesday GitHub repository. This is where you can find each week's dataset.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:10.000
I'm going to scroll down to find the link for this week's data.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:16.000
This week, we have data on emergency room wait times in the United States.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Here we can see how to read in the data with R and Python.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:23.000
And then you also have a data dictionary.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:30.000
So I'm just going to quickly look at the data dictionary to identify what aspects of the data I might want to display in my Shiny app.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:37.000
So I'm noticing that there is a state variable, a condition for which the patient is admitted, and some dates.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
So one thing you might want to do is visualize wait times for different conditions across states.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Okay, so now we're ready to head on over to Shiny Assistant.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Okay, so this is Shiny Assistant. It's available for both Shiny for R and Shiny for Python.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Over here, you can ask Shiny Assistant questions about Shiny, ask it to build a Shiny app for you, or ask it to debug an existing Shiny app that you have.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:09.000
We're going to use Shiny Assistant to build an app that uses this week's TidyTuesday emergency room data.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:17.000
But before I give Shiny Assistant the actual TidyTuesday dataset, I'm going to have it build an app just conceptually about emergency room data,

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:25.000
just to get something simple working, so I can visualize what I might want out of the Shiny app for this week's data.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:27.000
So here's the prompt I'm going to ask.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:33.000
I'm asking it to create a basic Shiny app with a sidebar, where there's one input where the user can select a variable to visualize,

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
and then on the main part of the app, there's a visualization.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.000
And then I'm saying just to create fake emergency room data.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:48.000
I could supply it with the TidyTuesday data right off the bat, but I want to sort of force Shiny Assistant to make something as simple as possible

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.000
before we're using the real data, which has a lot going on in it.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Okay, and then I'm saying just make the app as simple as possible.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:04.000
So I want something that's easy to understand, so that when I take that code and start development on my own,

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
I know what's going on and there hasn't been anything done that's unnecessarily complicated.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:19.000
Okay, so Shiny Assistant is generating the code over in the chat on the left,

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:28.000
but then also opening Shiny Live app, creating an app.py file, and then placing the code in that app.py file and running the app.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
So we can see the app that it made over here.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So it does have, like I asked, an input with different metrics to visualize, and then it visualizes those in the main content area.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Great, so this is pretty much what I asked for.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
It's a pretty simple app, but it's easy to understand.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
So now we're ready to ask it to use the real TidyTuesday data.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.000
So now I'm going to say, can you use the real data and provide it with the link?

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And then behind the scenes, I took a closer look at the data and I realized that it's in a long format.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:10.000
So there's a condition column, which stores information about where the patient was and what kind of care they were getting.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.000
So some of the values of condition are emergency room, but some are like sepsis care or vaccination.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And then there's a measure ID column and a value column or measure value column or something,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:29.000
where measure ID contains different things that you're measuring, like wait time or maximum wait time,

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:33.000
and then the value stores the actual value of that measure.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:34.000
So it's in a long format.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
So I'm just going to give Shiny Assistant that extra context.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Okay, so I want it to only use rows where condition is emergency department,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
and then I'm giving it some extra information about the columns.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
I think this is actually measure ID column.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:51.000
And then I'm also going to give Shiny Assistant the data dictionary.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:55.000
So I just copy and pasted this from the TidyTuesday repository.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Okay.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:07.000
So it was a lot of information for Shiny Assistant, but we are using real data that I haven't explored that much.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
So I just want to give it as much context as possible.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
Okay, so it made us a new app, but we're getting an error.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
So one really nice thing about Shiny Assistant is that I can just feed it back this error

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:28.000
and have it debug it itself instead of trying to do it on my own.

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:35.000
So let's see what it says.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.000
It's going to regenerate hopefully working code and then rerun the new app.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:41.000
Great.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
Okay, so this time it worked.

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And see, now we're using our actual TidyTuesday data.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:55.000
We can select different metrics that are tracked for the emergency department,

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
and that's visualizing that metric for all of the states.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:00.000
So this is basically what I asked for.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:04.000
It doesn't look great right now, but we can keep iterating on it.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:09.000
So I'm going to see what happens if I ask Shiny Assistant to make some changes.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
So let's say I only want to visualize the data for a certain amount of states.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:16.000
This is kind of a lot of states for one plot.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:17.000
I can't really see their names.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:23.000
I could try to fix that, but maybe I'm only interested in a handful of the states.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:46.000
Let's ask it to add an input for the states.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.000
Okay, so I've asked it to add a selectize input

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.000
so that the user can select which states they want to visualize.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:54.000
Okay, great.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So this is already easier to see.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So I can add states and or remove them,

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:09.000
and now the user can select both the metric that they want to see

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
and the states that they want to see that metric for.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
Okay, so this is a great start to a Shiny app.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
It's not super polished or super finished,

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
but Shiny Assistant helped me get to a working, useful Shiny app very quickly,

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
and I now have a great starting point for continued development.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
So I could either continue working on this in Shiny Assistant

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:36.000
or I could take this code to my local IDE and continue development there.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.000
One other thing I want to point out is that you can ask Shiny Assistant

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
just general questions about Shiny or about your app.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:47.000
So let's say I want to understand something that's happening in the app.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So maybe I want to just know more about the selectize input.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:02.000
I can ask Shiny Assistant, and it'll just give me some more information,

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.000
and it also knows about the code that I'm writing,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:09.000
so it can tell me specifically what's happening in my own code that it just wrote for me.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:14.000
So this is really helpful for learning more about Shiny as you're developing Shiny apps.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So I encourage you to check out Shiny Assistant,

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:22.000
whether for TidyTuesday, PietyTuesday, or some other Shiny app that you would like to work on.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.000
It's really helpful for quickly developing and iterating on Shiny apps

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:30.000
as well as for just learning more about Shiny.

